<article>
    <h1>BTS named En&#xAD;ter&#xAD;tainer of the Year by Time mag&#xAD;a&#xAD;zine</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201212/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-12-12"><time>2020-12-12</time></a>
        - <span>LIFE | MONITORING</span>
        - <span role="byline">REUTERS</span>
    </section>

    <p>K-pop group BTS were named en­ter­tainer of the year by Time mag­a­zine on Thurs­day, cap­ping a break­through year in the United States for the South Korean boy band.</p>
    <p>The seven-mem­ber band, which made their de­but in 2013, have be­come one of the world’s most pop­u­lar, thanks to their up­beat dance­wor­thy songs, army of ador­ing fans and pos­i­tive non-con­tro­ver­sial mes­sages.</p>
    <p>Last month, the band got the first ma­jor Grammy Award nom­i­na­tion for a K-pop band and, in the sum­mer, their English-lan­guage sin­gle Dy­na­mite be­came the band’s first to de­but at No. 1 on the Bill­board Hot 100 charts.</p>
    <p>“BTS isn’t just the big­gest K-pop act on the charts. They’ve be­come the big­gest band in the world – full stop,” Time writer Raisa Bruner wrote in a pro­file of the group on Thurs­day.</p>
    <p>“And they did it in a year de­fined by set­backs, one in which the world hit pause and ev­ery­one strug­gled to main­tain their con­nec­tions.”</p>
    <p>Twit­ter said this week that BTS “con­tin­ues to reign as most tweeted about mu­si­cians” in the US for a fourth straight year.</p>
    <p>The group shared an ex­clu­sive per­for­mance of their hit song Dy­na­mite in a tele­vi­sion spe­cial on Thurs­day, dur­ing which Time mag­a­zine an­nounced US Pres­i­den­t­elect Joe Bi­den and Vice-Pres­i­dent-elect Ka­mala Harris as Per­son of the Year.</p>

